ODE X.

‘Tua wise sailor is neither tempted too far out to sea nor frightened on to rocks and shallows. One who has learnt to love the golden mean neither has a huvel witha roof falling in nor a palace that would attract the evil eye. The higher the seat the greater the fall. The wise man is prepared for fortune to change like everything else. Be braye and hopeful if things are against you, and so. too, do not spread all your sails because the wind chauces to be favourable.'

Horace recommends moderatiori of life and manners. Professedly it is a meon that he praises; bnt it is clear throughout that it is excess that he deprecates; the danger of defect is uot really before his mind. This is shown in the first part of the Ode by omission—the hypothesis would require a stanna corresponding to st. 3 to illustrate the danger of being too low, as that illustrates the danger of being too high-in the second part by the stress laid on the altemative least contemplated, under cover of which the poet at last ventures to put plainly the lesson on which his heart is really set.
